50|$|A theory sustains that is {{feasible}} to typify <b>letter</b> <b>of</b> <b>credit</b> as a collateral contract for a third-party beneficiary because <b>letters</b> <b>of</b> <b>credit</b> are {{prompted by the}} buyer’s necessity and in application {{of the theory of}} Jean Domat the cause <b>of</b> a <b>letter</b> <b>of</b> <b>credit</b> is that a bank issue a <b>credit</b> in favor <b>of</b> a seller to release the buyer of his obligation to pay directly to the seller with legal tender. There are in fact three different entities participating in the <b>letter</b> <b>of</b> <b>credit</b> transaction: the seller, the buyer, and the banker. Therefore, a <b>letter</b> <b>of</b> <b>credit</b> theoretically fits as a collateral contract accepted by conduct, or in other words, an implied-in-fact contract.|$|R
